default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultAppendix A: defaultAchieving better balanced growth – a role for R&amp;Ddefault&#xa0;default&#xa0;
defaultA1.
default 
defaultAs the UK came out of recession, a consensus emerged that we could not continue to grow in the same way 
defaultwe
default had done in the previous 15 years. A better balanced economy would be one where growth was based on innovation, investment and trade rather than cons
defaultumption.
default At the time, 
defaultforecasters were optimistic that this kind of growth could be achieved, but the recovery did not materialise as expected and business investment in particular remains well below its pre-recession average. 
default&#xa0;
defaultA2.
default 
defaultIn 2012
default,
default EEF 
defaultpublished 
defaultT
defaulthe 
defaultRoute to Growth
default, our take on what an Industrial Strate
defaultgy 
defaultthat would deliver better-balance
defaultd
default growth 
defaultfor the UK should look like.
default 
defaultThe central principle was that government should to
default take an economy-wide approach
default towards 
defaultcreating the climate and conditions 
defaultthat would enable
default businesses in all sectors to grow through investment and exporting.
default&#xa0;
defaultA3.
default 
defaultThe
default UK has significant strengths on which to build, including a diverse and innovative manufacturing base and strong science capabilities. An Industrial Strategy must se
defaultek to build on these strengths
default with a set of clear ambitions which lay out what government is looking to achieve.
default&#xa0;
defaultA4.
default 
defaultEEF’s vision for the economy is based on achieving four key ambitions:
